          <h3><a id="Q2">How is vCruit different from putting my videos on YouTube?</a></h3>
          <p>
            <strong>Reason 1: YouTube is designed to keep a viewer on YouTube to watch more videos and click on adds, which lowers your conversion rates.</strong> You want clear and visible call to action buttons that drive viewers of your videos to respond to you, look at your other job postings, visit your website, or share your video with someone else.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Reason 2: The wide variety of content on YouTube detracts from your professionally oriented content.</strong> Do you really want your video to be next to a video of some guy shaving his cat?
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Reason 3: YouTube's analytics are more macro oriented.</strong> While YouTube does offer extensive analytics in many areas, it lacks important granular data on individual viewers that you want.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Conclusion: YouTube can serve as a secondary distribution channel, but is not the most effective primary location to host your videos.</strong>
          </p>
